kshetram]]'' (2019, Dubbed version)\n*''[[Paper Boy]]'' (2018)\n*''[[Yevadu]]'' (2014)\n*''[[Cameraman Ganga Tho Rambabu]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofap.com/cinema/pawan-kalyans-cameraman-ganga-tho-rambabu-nizam-rights-sold/|title=Timesofap Redirecting ...|publisher=}}</ref> (2012)\n*''[[Mahesh Khaleja]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Puli (2010 film)|Komaram Puli]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Leader (film)|Leader]]'' (2010)\n*''[[Magadheera]]'' (2009)\n*''[[Ghajini (2008 film)|Ghajini]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Parugu]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Jalsa]]'' (2008)\n*''[[Desamuduru]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Stalin (2006 film)|Stalin]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Happy (2006 film)|Happy]]'' (2006)\n*''[[Andarivaadu]]'' (2005)\n*''[[Johnny (2003 film)|Johnny]]'' (2003)\n*''[[Annayya (2000 film)|Annayya]]'' (2000)\n*''[[Iddaru Mitrulu (1999 film)|Iddaru Mitrulu]]'' (1999)\n*''[[Paradesi (1998 film)|Paradesi]]'' (1998)\n*''[[Bavagaru Bagunnara?]] (1998)\n*''[[Pelli Sandadi]]'' (1996)\n*''[[Big Boss (film)|Big Boss]]'' (1995)\n*''[[Rowdy Alludu]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Gang Leader]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Stuartpuram Police Station]]'' (1991)\n*''[[Raja Vikramarka]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Kodama Simham]]'' (1990)\n*''[[Attaku Yamudu Ammayiki Mogudu]]'' (1989)\n*''[[Trinetrudu]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Khaidi No. 786]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Yamudiki Mogudu]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Rudraveena (film)|Rudraveena]]'' (1988)\n*''[[Jebu Donga]]'' (1987)\n*''[[Pasivadi Pranam]]'' (1987)\n\n==Distribution==\nOver the last 15 years, Geetha Film Distributors (GFD), a subsidiary of  Geetha Arts has released over 300 Telugu, Hindi and English films in Andhra Pradesh and is one of the leading distributors in the state. Geetha Arts is one company in Andhra Pradesh that has a studio-style functioning of having a production wing along with distribution channels.  Over the years, GFD has earned a reputation of being a highly transparent company serving small and big producers, all alike. Geetha Film Distributors (GFD), a wholly owned subsidiary of Allu Entertainment Private Limited.\nGhajini 2008 was biggest Hit in Geetha Arts distribution which collected {{INRConvert|115|c}} domestic nett.The rights of domestic markets were bought  for {{INRConvert|53|c}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.komarampuli.tollywoodblog.in/2010/05/komaram-puli-worldwide-release-through.html|title=Komaram Puli worldwide Release Through Geetha Arts ~ Komaram Puli|publisher=}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official|http://geethaarts.com/}}\n* {{IMDb company|id=0054903}}\n* {{YouTube|user=geethaarts|Geetha Arts}}\n\n[[Category:Film production companies based in Hyderabad, India]]\n[[Category:Film production companies of India]]\n[[Category:Indian film studios]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toGentleman (disambiguation)(link changed toThe Gentleman (film)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geetha_Arts"}
{"title_page": "1428 Elm Street", "text_new": "{{Infobox fictional location\n| name          = 1428 Elm Street\n| image         =\n| image_size    =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| source        = [[A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)|A Nightmare on Elm Street]]\n| alt_name      = [The] Elm Street House\n| first         = ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street]]'' (1984)\n| last          = ''[[Freddy vs Jason]]'' (2003)\n| creator       = [[Wes Craven]]\n| genre         = [[Horror film]]\n| type          = Residential house\n| blank_label1  = Location\n| blank_data1   = Springwood, [[Ohio]]\n| blank_label2  = Street\n| blank_data2   = Elm Street\n| ruler         = \n| characters    = {{bulleted list|[[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Nancy Thompson]]|[[Jesse Walsh]]|[[List of A Nightmare on Elm Street characters#Lori Campbell|Lori Campbell]]|[[Freddy Krueger]]<br>([[#The house as Freddy's home|possibly]])}}\n}}\n\n{{for|the historic house in [[Arkansas]]|Elm Street House}}\n'''1428 Elm Street''', also known as '''[the] Elm Street House''', is a fictional residential house and street address in Springwood, [[Ohio]], and is an important location in the ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)|A Nightmare on Elm Street]]'' [[Media franchise|franchise]], where it's been the home of [[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Nancy Thompson]] and her mother, later [[Jesse Walsh]] and his family, and finally [[List of A Nightmare on Elm Street characters#Lori Campbell|Lori Campbell]] and her father throughout the film series. It has also been hinted at to have been [[Freddy Krueger]]'s home when he was alive. It further appears in some form in nearly all the films as well as literature, comics, video games and music videos. The house, like Nancy, [[Tina Gray (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Tina Gray]], [[Kristen Parker]] as well as their mutual tormentor and eventual murderer [[Freddy Krueger]], were all conceived by the late horror legend [[Wes Craven]].\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===Films===\n\n1428 Elm Street is first introduced in ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street]]'' (1984), where it is owned by Marge Thompson, who lives there with her teenage daughter [[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Nancy]]. There is seemingly nothing out of the ordinary about the house at the time, but this changes when Nancy and her friends starts to have a series of nightmares all featuring the same disfigured, menacing stalker, culminating in Nancy's best friend [[Tina Gray (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Tina Gray]] being slaughtered in her bed by an unseen assailer in the Gray's house on the same street. Piecing together the lore surrounding [[Freddy Krueger]], Nancy learns that her parents along with others [[Lynching|lynched]] and torched Freddy to death after he had murdered around 20 kids in the neighborhood; they also hid his old murder weapon, a glove with knives attached to it, in a boiler in the basement of the Thompson's home. Nancy finds a way to bring Freddy out of her dreams and confronts him in 1428 Elm Street, luring him through a series of [[boobytrap]]s and setting him in fire. He is temporarily vanquished when Nancy convince him and herself that he have no power over her unless she believes he has, and tells him that she takes back the energy she gave him.<ref name=\"N1 film\">{{cite AV media|people=[[Wes Craven]] (director)|title=[[A Nightmare on Elm Street]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=[[New Line Cinema]]|date=1984}}</ref> The  comics ''Nightmares on Elm Street'' reveals that after this, Nancy moved away from Springwood and went to college in the span between the first film and ''Dream Warriors''.<ref name=\"comic2\">{{cite comic | writer=Andy Mangels | penciller=Tony Harris | inker=Vickie Williams | editor=David Campiti | story=Eternal Evil | title=Nightmares on Elm Street | volume=1 |issue=#2 | date=November 1991 | publisher=Innovation Publishing | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Comics/nightmares-on-elm-street-2/}}</ref>\n\nThe sequel ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 2: Freddy's Revenge]]'' (1985) insinuates that the house had stood unoccupied following the conclusion of the first film. After about five years, the Walsh family moved in, but Freddy's spirit lingered as a residual memory in the house, geographically restricted to it for the moment, and started to invade the dreams of the new occupant [[Jesse Walsh]] as he did with Nancy, now with the additional goal of [[Demonic possession|possessing]] him and making Jesse kill for him.<ref name=\"N2 film\">{{cite AV media|people=[[Jack Sholder]] (director)|title=[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 2: Freddy's Revenge]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=1985}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 3: Dream Warriors]]'' (1987), Freddy seems to have \"adopted\" the house in the dreamworld, luring his victims there even when their dreams does not start in the house. Freddy increasingly tended to blend the house together with the old factory he worked in and brought his victims to while he was alive; the factory was the place he lured Nancy into in her nightmare in school in the first film.<ref name=\"N3 film\">{{cite video|people=[[Chuck Russell]] (Director)|title=[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 3: Dream Warriors]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=1987}}</ref> By the time of ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 4: The Dream Master|The Dream Master]]'', the real life 1428 Elm Street has become an uninhabited and boarded up ghost house since the Walsh's moved out at an unknown date - with ''Dream Warriors'' having left their fates unresolved - and would continue being so for many years. Before the events of ''Dream Warriors'', [[Kristen Parker]] builds a model of the house she keeps seeing in her nightmares. After being admitted to and later released from the Westin Hills Asylum, she had come to consider the house to be Freddy's \"home\" due to its reoccurrence in her nightmares. Before Freddy kills Kristen, her dreams would see her return to the dream-house and its boiler room many times, even when Freddy was dormant.<ref name=\"N4 film\">{{cite video|people=[[Renny Harlin]] (Director)|title=[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 4: The Dream Master]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=1988}}</ref> Though not seen in reality in ''The Dream Child'', the dream version of the house is part of the vistas seen by [[Alice Johnson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Alice Johnson]] in her struggles with Freddy. By this stage Freddy had further perverted the dream-house into a [[M. C. Escher]]-esque labyrinth by also integrating the Westin Hills Asylum and the Dream Church from the two previous films into it.<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child | type=shooting script | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Files/nightmare-on-elm-street-5-script.pdf | date=1989 | access-date=March 10, 2020 | author=John Skipp, Craig Spector, Leslie Bohem, David J. Schow | via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion}}</ref><ref name=\"N5 film\">{{cite video|people=[[Stephen Hopkins (director)|Stephen Hopkins]] (Director)|title=[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=1989}}</ref> In ''Freddy's Dead'', the house was visited by protagonists such as John Doe and Maggie Burroughs and the film often hinted of the idea that Freddy and his family had once lived there when he was alive.<ref name=\"N6 film\">{{cite video|people=Rachel Talalay (Director)|title=[[Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=1991}}</ref>\n\nThe house also appears in the climax of ''[[Wes Craven's New Nightmare]]'' (1994), when a metafictional [[Heather Langenkamp]] channels her in-universe character Nancy Thompson and Heather's house followingly turn into 1428 Elm Street.<ref name=\"N7 film\">{{cite video |people=Wes Craven (Director) |title=[[Wes Craven's New Nightmare]] |medium=DVD |location=United States |publisher=New Line Cinema |date=1994}}</ref> In ''[[Freddy vs Jason]]'' (2003), the house is occupied by Dr. Campbell and his daughter Lori; Freddy murdered Mrs. Campbell in their bedroom after the events of ''[[Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare]]'' took place.<ref name=\"FvJ film\">{{cite AV media|people=[[Ronny Yu]] (director)|title=[[Freddy vs. Jason]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=2003}}</ref> In a scene that was cut from the theatrical film, Lori scratches the repainted door to discover the original red painting underneath.<ref name=\"fvjds\">{{cite web | title=Freddy vs. Jason deleted scene - At death's door | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-fa-wg0H1Dc | date=April 5, 2008 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | author=[[New Line Cinema]] / Nightmare Companion (uploader) | via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n===Other appearances===\n\n====Halloween Horror Nights====\n\nThe house was one of the haunted houses at [[Universal Orlando]]'s [[Halloween Horror Nights|Halloween Horror Nights: Carnival of Carnage]] in 2007; the exterior had been modeled after the worn down dream version from ''Dream Warriors'' and ''The Dream Master''. It was also recreated for [[Universal Studios Hollywood]]'s 2008 event called \"Nightmare on Elm Street: Home Sweet Hell\"<ref>{{cite web | title=Hollywood horror show isn't for the faint of heart | url=http://archive.vcstar.com/lifestyle/hollywood-horror-show-isnt-for-the-faint-of-heart-ep-372911556-352419501.html | website=[[Ventura County Star]] | author=Rick Bentley | date=October 19, 2008 | access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> The house appeared again as a setting during Halloween Horror Nights 25 in 2015 at its \"Freddy vs Jason\" event.<ref>{{cite web | title=Halloween Horror Nights 25 - Freddy vs Jason | url=https://aminoapps.com/c/horror/page/blog/halloween-horror-nights-25-freddy-vs-jason/J8MF_dur2nog0L7wDjLJg4jbm8N2D2r | date=July 16, 2018 | access-date=March 8, 2020 | author=firstclasshorror | website=Amino Apps}}</ref>\n\n====Literature and comics====\n\nIn the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' comics first two issues, set in 1990, Nancy Thompson's former roommate Cybil Houch sees the house in her recent nightmares about someone who appears to be [[Jack the Ripper]]; the sight of the house leads her to track down Nancy only to find that she died three years ago. Nancy also uses her own version of the house as her \"safe haven\" in the dream world.<ref name=\"comic1\">{{cite comic | writer=[[Andy Mangels]] | penciller=Tony Harris | inker=Vickie Williams | editor=David Campiti | story=Yours Truly, Freddy Krueger | title=Nightmares on Elm Street | volume=1 |issue=#1 | date=September 1991 | publisher=[[Innovation Publishing]] | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Comics/nightmares-on-elm-street-1/}}</ref><ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite web | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/features/timeline/ | title=Timeline | via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion | access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> The house is seen in ''[[Freddy vs. Jason vs. Ash]]'' #5, where a fight between [[Jason Voorhees]] and [[Ash Williams]] causes it to collapse.<ref>{{cite comic | title=[[Freddy vs. Jason vs. Ash]] | issue=#5 | date=April 2008 | writer=[[Jeff Katz]] | cowriters=James Kuhoric | artist=[[Jason Craig]] | colorist=Thomas Mason | letterer=Jared K. Fletcher | editor=Scott Peterson | publisher=[[WildStorm]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the short story \"Asleep at the Wheel\" by Brian Hodge from the anthology book ''The Nightmares on Elm Street: Freddy Krueger's Seven Sweetest Dreams'' (1991), a band that has named themselves \"Nancy Thompson Gravewatch\" decides to spend the night at 1428 Elm Street, which \"has sat idle and abandoned and vacant and boarded over for years\" as described in the story. The band's idea with staying at the house is to confront their inner darkness and make it their own. They are warned against it by Nancy's ghost, but the band refuses to listen and are picked off one by one by Freddy.<ref name=\"ssd1\">{{cite book | author=Brian Hodge | editor=Martin Harry Greenberg | date=1991-10-15 | title=The Nightmares on Elm Street: Freddy Krueger's Seven Sweetest Dreams | chapter=Asleep at the Wheel | publisher = St. Martin's Press | isbn =0-312-92585-9}}</ref> In the short story \"Dead Highway, Lost Roads\" from the same book the house alongside with most of Elm Street has been leveled to the ground and replaced with a shopping mall to help bury the bad reputation that it had gained; Alice Johnson lives nearby, to keep a vigil on Freddy's activities.<ref name=\"ssd2\">{{cite book | author=Philip Nutman | editor=Martin Harry Greenberg | date=1991-10-15 | title=The Nightmares on Elm Street: Freddy Krueger's Seven Sweetest Dreams | chapter=Dead Highway, Lost Roads | pages=172-239 | publisher=St. Martin's Press | isbn=9780312925857}}</ref> In the novel ''A Nightmare on Elm Street: Suffer the Children'', taking place after the events of ''Freddy vs. Jason'', Lori Campbell has moved out of Springwood and 1428 Elm Street is now occupied by Alexandra Corwin and her mother.<ref>{{cite book | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street: Suffer the Children | author=[[David Bishop (writer)|David Bishop]] | date=April 26, 2005 | isbn=1844161722 | publisher=[[Black Flame (publisher)|Black Flame]] | pages=416}}</ref>\n\n====Video games====\n\nThe house is the central setting of an online game called \"Escape from 1428 Elm Street\".<ref name=\"arcadespot\">{{cite web | title=Escape From 1428 Elm Street | url=https://arcadespot.com/game/escape-from-1428-elm-street/ | type=online game | access-date=March 8, 2020 | website=Arcade Spot}}</ref>\n\n====Music videos====\n\nIn the [[music video]] for [[The Fat Boys]]' ''[[Are You Ready for Freddy]]'', the band has to stay one night in the house of one of the Boys' recently deceased \"Uncle Frederick\".<ref>{{cite web | title=The Fat Boys - Are You Ready For Freddy? | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XDUl5Ke5jbM | author=[[The Fat Boys]] | date=August 19, 1988 | via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> The music video for [[Dokken]]'s ''[[Dream Warriors (song)|Dream Warriors]]'' song is mostly set in the nightmare version of the house, as visited by [[Kristen Parker]] in the ''Dream Warriors'' film.<ref name=\"dokken\">{{Cite AV media | title=Dokken \u2013 \"Dream Warriors\" (Official Music Video) | via=YouTube | people=[[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]], [[Jeff Pilson]], [[Patricia Arquette]], [[Robert Englund]] | date=February 10, 1987 | access-date=March 16, 2020 | publisher=[[Elektra Records|Elektra]] | medium=music video | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=noLPhZvcBpw}}</ref>\n\n====Unrealized projects====\nThe house has been featured in several alternate screenplays that was never filmed. For the third film which became ''Dream Warriors'', Robert Englund wrote his own treatment ''Freddy's Funhouse'', where Freddy had claimed the house for his own in the dream world, setting up [[booby trap]]s against dreamers like Nancy did against him.<ref>{{cite web | title=Freddy's Funhouse: Digging into Robert Englund's Unmade Treatment for 'Nightmare on Elm Street 3' | url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3532787/freddys-funhouse-digging-robert-englunds-unmade-treatment-nightmare-elm-street-3/ | date=November 9, 2018 | author=Nat Brehmer | website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] | access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> In an alternate script for ''A Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child'' by John Skipp & Craig Spector, a character\nis painting a drawing of the Elm Street house, only to be interrupted by a bulldozer leveling the legally condemned building to the ground to make way for the Elm St. Mall.<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street V: The Dream Child | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Files/nightmare-on-elm-street-5-original-script.pdf | type=screenplay | author=[[John Skipp]] & Craig Spector | date=January 7, 1989 | access-date=March 17, 2020 | via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion}}</ref> In the original script for ''Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare'' by Michael Almereyda, a character walks up to the house and removes plates of the mailbox with the name Williams, the last owners, to reveal the name Thompson underneath, which in turn has the name Krueger underneath it.<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street 6 | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Files/nightmare-on-elm-street-6-alt-script.pdf | type=screenplay | author=Rachel Talalay and Michael Almereyda | via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion | access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> Several alternate drafts for ''Freddy vs Jason'' featured the house, including scripts by [[Peter Briggs]], [[Ethan Reiff and Cyrus Voris|Reiff/Voris]] and Abernathy/[[David J. Schow|Schow]]; in the latter, a rundown 1428 Elm Street is blown up following a shootout between a SWAT team and a twisted Freddy-worshipping cultist group, culminating in the latter detonating a bomb in the basement.<ref name=\"slashofthetitans\">{{cite book | title=Slash of the Titans: The Road to Freddy vs Jason | author=Dustin McNeill | date=March 25, 2017 | publisher=Harker Press | asin=B06XVSCY6C | isbn=0692033491 | url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Slash_of_the_Titans.html?id=omSNAQAACAAJ}}</ref>\n\nIn [[David Bishop (writer)|David Bishop]]'s finished but never published sequel to his novel ''A Nightmare on Elm Street: Suffer the Children'', called ''House of 100 Maniacs'', Alexandra Corwin was deemed insane, incriminated for eight murders in truth committed by Freddy and had to spend five years in a maximum security psychiatric ward before being released, brainwashed into thinking that Freddy was nothing but a delusion of hers. As a final part of her therapy, her psychotherapist convinces her that she must go to her former home, the now once again boarded up 1428 Elm Street (now scheduled for demolition), in order to face her demons. The house however attracts many who are intrigued by its reputation as a haunted house, providing Freddy with yet another batch of victims to slaughter. Alex and a girl named Jenny survives, while in the epilogue the house would finally have been demolished. The unpublished novel would also have established that Freddy did live at 1428 as a child.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Nightmare that never was | url=http://viciousimagery.blogspot.com/2006/11/nightmare-that-never-was.html | website=Vicious Imagery | author=[[David Bishop (writer)|David Bishop]] | date=November 27, 2006 | access-date=March 16, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316005934/http://viciousimagery.blogspot.com/2006/11/nightmare-that-never-was.html | archive-date=March 16, 2020 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nFrom the first film to the sequels, the Elm Street House develops from simply being the place where the action takes to becoming the embodiment of Freddy in the physical world, taking on the characteristics of a classic [[haunted house]] and acting as a portal between the waking life and the [[Dream world (plot device)|dream world]] when characters steps in through the door of the house.<ref name=\"styleandform\">{{cite book | title=Style and Form in the Hollywood Slasher Film | last=Shimabukuro | first=Karra | editor-last=Clayton | editor-first=Wickham | publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]] | year=2016 | isbn=9781137496478 | pages=60-61 | chapter=I Framed Freddy: Functional Aesthetics in the ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' series | chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DWPeCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA49}}</ref> In the original script from ''Dream Warriors'', the house seen by the Elm Street children in their nightmares is revealed to not be 1428 Elm Street, but a ranch house where Freddy was born; this idea was omitted in the theatrical film.<ref name=\"dworiginal\">{{Cite web|url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Files/nightmare-on-elm-street-3-wes-craven-script.pdf|last1=Craven | first1=Wes | author1-link=Wes Craven | last2=Wagner | first2=Bruce | author2-link=Bruce Wagner | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street 3: Dream Warriors (original script)|date=June 16, 1986|via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> The novelization ''The Nightmares on Elm Street Parts 1, 2, 3: The Continuing Story'', written by Jeffrey Cooper, uses the original script rather than the film script; thus, the ranch house also appears in the ''Dream Warriors'' chapter in the book.<ref name=\"jcooper\">{{cite book | title=The Nightmares on Elm Street parts 1, 2 & 3: The Continuing Story | chapter=[[centralwikia:w:c:nightmareonelmstreet:A Nightmare on Elm Street 3: Dream Warriors (novelization)|Dream Warriors]] | last=Cooper | isbn=978-0312905170 | first=Jeffrey | publisher=St Martins Pr | date=February 1, 1987}}</ref> A non-canonical alternate backstory for 1428 Elm Street was featured in ''The Life and Death of Freddy Krueger'' contained within Cooper's novelization, where the house is described to have once have been a mental asylum where Freddy was born to an unnamed [[Schizophrenia|schizophrenic]] female patient who died in childbirth;<ref>{{cite web | title=The Life and Death of Freddy Krueger | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/the-life-and-death-of-freddy-krueger/ | date=February 1, 1987 | access-date=March 13, 2020 | via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion}}</ref> the former asylum at 1428 is also present in Cooper's novelization of ''Dream Warriors'', where it's called the Hathaway House.<ref name=\"jcooper\" />\n\n===Filming locations===\n<!-- Out-of-universe description --->\nThe house from the original film was filmed at a private home in 1428 North Genesee Avenue in [[Los Angeles]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Gary Wayne |url=http://www.seeing-stars.com/Locations/80sLocations2.shtml |title=The Nightmare on Elm Street House (photo) |website=Seeing-stars.com |access-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404120102/http://www.seeing-stars.com/Locations/80sLocations2.shtml |archivedate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> which was constructed in the year 1919;<ref name=\"horrorenthusiast\">{{cite web | title=Where Is the Real Nightmare On Elm Street House Located? | url=https://horrorenthusiast.com/index.php/bloody-tabloid/nightmare-on-elm-street-franchise/49-where-is-the-real-nightmare-on-elm-street-house-located | date=January 18, 2018 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | website=Horror Enthusiast | author=Mr. Cleaver}}</ref> on the other side of the street stands house 1419 which was used as the Lantz family home in the film, where it was also located on the other side of the street.<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street (1984) | url=http://www.set-jetter.com/ontheset/anightmareonelmstreet | date=July 6, 2015 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | website=Jet-Setter}}</ref> House 1428 was also used in ''Freddy's Revenge'' and ''Wes Craven's New Nightmare''.<ref name=\"1428comp\">{{cite web | title=1428 Elm Street | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/features/1428-elm-street/ | website=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion | access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> On [[Bloody Disgusting]], it has been suggested that the house was also used for pickup scenes in the extended TV version of the original ''[[Halloween (1978 film)|Halloween]]'' film by [[John Carpenter]], pointing out the common presence of a decorative wooden horse in the filmed scenes and the pre-renovation house at 1428 North Genesee Avenue as a clue to this.<ref>{{cite web | title=Was the Iconic \u2018Nightmare on Elm Street\u2019 House Used Years Prior in \u2018Halloween\u2019? | url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3591404/iconic-nightmare-elm-street-house-used-years-prior-halloween/ | date=October 28, 2019 | access-date=March 8, 2020 | author=Alex Aronson | website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]}}</ref> Sean Clark, host of ''Horrors Hallowed Grounds'', was able to visit the house in 2006 before massive renovations completely erased any likeness to the interior as seen in the films. According to Clark, Nancy's room as seen in ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' had not been a room in the actual house, but one inside a studio set. Carpenter however had gained permission to film inside the actual house, whereas [[Heather Langenkamp]] as Nancy was only inside the house at 1428 North Genesee Avenue for scenes where she's looking out from her bedroom window.<ref>{{cite web | title=Evidence Suggests \u2018A Nightmare On Elm Street\u2019 House Is In \u2018Halloween\u2019 | url=https://www.screengeek.net/2019/10/29/a-nightmare-on-elm-street-house-halloween-movie/ | author=Jacob Dressler | website=Screen Geek | date=October 29, 2019 | access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Someone was asking how I found out that Nancy's house... | url=https://www.facebook.com/malfuncsean/posts/10155799496887031 | author=Sean Clark | via=[[Facebook]] | date=October 23, 2018 | access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe house was put up for sale during 2006.<ref>{{cite web | title=For Sale: Nightmare on Elm Street House | url=http://www.cinematical.com/2006/09/25/for-sale-nightmare-on-elm-street-house/ | date=September 25, 2006 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509063149/http://www.cinematical.com/2006/09/25/for-sale-nightmare-on-elm-street-house/ | archive-date=May 9, 2007 | url-status=dead | website=Cinematical}}</ref> It was in a state of negligence and worn down when Angie Hill bought it in 2008; she paid $1.15 million for the house then and began a year-long renovation.<ref name=\"ttred\">{{cite web | title=Sold Fast! The Nightmare on Elm Street House! | url=https://www.toptenrealestatedeals.com/weekly-ten-best-home-deals/home/sold-fast-the-nightmare-on-elm-street-house | website=TopTenRealEstateDeals | access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> According to Hill, the previous owners had neglected it to such an extant that it might have been the slummiest house on the street. She preserved its facade throughout the renovation to retain much of its original looks.<ref name=\"horrorenthusiast\" /> Hill renovated as much as 90% of the original interior.<ref>{{cite web | title=1428 North Genesee Avenue Featured on Aol Real Estate | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/1428-north-genesee-avenue-featured-on-aol-real-estate/ | date=October 27, 2012 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | website=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion}}</ref> The house switched owners in 2013 for the price of $2.1 million.<ref name=\"ttred\" /> Heather Langenkamp and Sean Clark visited the house at 1428 North Genesee Avenue in the franchise documentary ''[[Never Sleep Again: The Elm Street Legacy]]'' from 2010, where Hill explains that the original numbers spelling out 1428 had been stolen; the original font could not be replaced as it was no longer being manufactured.<ref name=\"neversleepagain\">{{cite web | title=Never Sleep Again: The Elm Street Legacy | url=https://www.amazon.com/Never-Sleep-Again-Street-Blu-ray/dp/B00G6TPQ1C/ | format=blu-ray | people=Robert Englund, Heather Langenkamp, Wes Craven, Lisa Wilcox, Alice Cooper, Andrew Kasch, Daniel Farrands, Thommy Hutson |website=Amazon.com |date=May 4, 2010 |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Heather and [[Robert Englund]] (Freddy Krueger) also revisited the house together in 2013,<ref>{{cite web | title='Nightmare' stars Robert Englund & Heather Langenkamp Return to Elm Street | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hlmdt5VE3Lk | date=March 8, 2013 | access-date=March 8, 2020 | author=David Weiner | via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>, while [[Lisa Wilcox]] (Alice Johnson) visited it in 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title=Join Lisa Wilcox (Alice Johnson) at the original Nightmare on Elm Street house. Los Angeles, CA | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SCuq_evUX20 | author=Lisa Wilcox | date=April 27, 2017 | access-date=March 8, 2020 | via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\nThe color of the front door was blue in ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'', but was painted blood red for ''Freddy's Revenge''; red would remain the preferred color throughout the franchise except for when Wes Craven had it restored to blue for ''[[Wes Craven's New Nightmare|New Nightmare]]'',<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street 2: Freddy's Revenge (1985) | url=http://www.set-jetter.com/ontheset/freddysrevenge | date=June 23, 2015 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | website=Set-Jetter}}</ref><ref name=\"N7 film\" /> which was once again filmed at 1428 North Genesee Avenue, whereas parts 3-6 had all used facade sets for the likeness of the house's front.<ref name=\"1428comp\" /> ''Freddy vs. Jason'' filmed with a different house than the other films as it was filmed in [[Vancouver]] and not Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web | title=Freddy vs. Jason (2003) | url=http://www.set-jetter.com/ontheset/freddyvsjason | date=November 28, 2015 | access-date=March 8, 2020 | website=Set-Jetter}}</ref> In the film, the door was originally red but had been painted over with yellow color.<ref name=\"fvjds\" /> According to production designer John Willett, the process of a finding a matching house in Vancouver was very difficult and earlier film teams from the ''Nightmare'' series had not preserved accurate drawing records that the new team could follow, but they eventually found a house that was an 80% match of its Los Angeles predecessor, and shot the scenes inside the house instead of a stage due to budget concerns.<ref name=\"CLM_book\">{{cite book|last = Bracke|first = Peter|title = Crystal Lake Memories - The Complete History of Friday the 13th|publisher = Titan Books|date = 2006-10-11|location = [[United Kingdom]]|page = 276|isbn = 1-84576-343-2}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\n===Setting===\n<!-- In-universe description --->\nThe house is located on Elm Street in the fictional town of Springwood in [[Ohio]]. In the script for the 1984 film, Wes Craven mentions Los Angeles in California as the setting and has Elm Street located in an unnamed suburb, but this information is left out of the film. The change to Ohio was possibly done as a homage to Wes Craven, who was born in Cleveland in Ohio.<ref>{{cite web | title=Series FAQ | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/features/series-faq/#04 | access-date=March 13, 2020 | website=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion}}</ref> The name Springwood and its change from suburb to town was introduced in ''Freddy's Revenge''.<ref name=\"N2 film\" /> The script to ''[[Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare]]'' humorously refers to Elm Street as \"''The supreme \"bad place\" of the universe. A street that ranks right there with \"The [[Flying Dutchman]]\", and \"The [[Bermuda Triangle]]\". The street that makes \"[[The Amityville Horror]]\" look like a Long Island tupperware party''.\"<ref>{{cite web | title=Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare \u2014 Scripts | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/films/freddys-dead-the-final-nightmare/freddys-dead-the-final-nightmare-scripts/ | website=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion | access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Many of the other characters in the series lives on Elm Street, such as Glen Lantz, Rick and [[Alice Johnson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Alice Johnson]], who refers to the child murders by pre-lynching Freddy Krueger to have happened \"right here on Elm Street\".<ref name=\"N5 film\" />\n\n===The house as Freddy's home===\n\nIn ''The Dream Master'', Kristen Parker refers to 1428 Elm Street as Freddy's home while visiting it in real life with her friends.<ref name=\"N4 film\" /> Halloween Horror Nights and various media such as \"Escape from 1428 Elm Street\" propagates the idea of the Thompson/Walsh house also having been Freddy's house.<ref name=\"arcadespot\" /> In the book \"''The Nightmare Never Ends: The Official History of Freddy Krueger and the \u2018Nightmare on Elm Street\u2019 Films''\", [[Andy Mangels]] supplies a \"Key to Map of Springwood\" which lists Elm Street residents and lists the Krueger's as living on 1665 Elm Street,<ref>{{cite web | title=Official map of Freddy Krueger\u2019s hometown of Springwood | url=https://see-throughiron.tumblr.com/post/127109586420/official-map-of-freddy-kruegers-hometown-of | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310221528/https://see-throughiron.tumblr.com/post/127109586420/official-map-of-freddy-kruegers-hometown-of | archive-date=March 10, 2020 | url-status=live | date=August 19, 2015 | access-date=March 10, 2020 | author=[[Andy Mangels]] | via=see-throughiron @ [[Tumblr]]}}</ref> and further argues that the houses might only look similar due to having the same designers, but the webmaster of Nightmare on Elm Street Companion argues that ''Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare'' definitely portrayed Freddy's original home as being in fact 1428 Elm Street, including a deleted scene where Maggie finds a hidden room in the basement of the house where Freddy kept all his weapons and tools designed for murder when he lived, and that the franchise has consistently referred to the house as \"Freddy's house\".<ref>{{cite web | title=The House Where Freddy Lives | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/the-house-where-freddy-lives/ | website=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion | access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> ''A Nightmare on Elm Street: The Beginning'', Andy Mangels' comic book sequel to ''Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare'' that was never finished due to the bankruptcy of [[Innovation Publishing]] and only saw two issues released, would have established that the reason for why Freddy is consistently drawn to 1428 Elm Street is because his original glove is hidden in its cellar.<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street: The Beginning (plot) | url=http://www.andymangels.com/Beginning_plot.pdf | author=[[Andy Mangels]] | website=Andymangels.com | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007013617/http://www.andymangels.com/Beginning_plot.pdf | date=October 22, 1991 | archive-date=October 7, 2009 | url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe house has been referred to as \"beyond iconic\",<ref name=\"cosplaychris\">{{cite web | title=Filming Locations: A Nightmare on Elm Street (1984) | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=123&v=22WnYtcWQgI&feature=emb_logo | author=Cosplay Chris | via=[[YouTube]] | date=July 30, 2018 | access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> \"one of the most legendary horror homes in movies\"<ref name=\"aol2012\">{{cite web | title=The House in 'A Nightmare on Elm Street' Was Truly Scary Before Angie Hill Rehabbed It | url=http://realestate.aol.com/blog/2012/10/12/the-house-in-a-nightmare-on-elm-street-was-truly-scary-before/ | author=Graham Wood | website=Aol Real Estate | date=October 12, 2012 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121213171733/http://realestate.aol.com/blog/2012/10/12/the-house-in-a-nightmare-on-elm-street-was-truly-scary-before/ | archive-date=December 13, 2012 | url-status=dead}}</ref> and \"the star of ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''\".<ref name=\"ihorror\">{{cite web | title=Every Town Has An Elm Street: A Look At 1428 Elm Street. | url=https://www.ihorror.com/every-town-has-an-elm-street-a-look-at-1428-elm-street/ | website=iHorror | author=Ryan T. Cusick | date=June 22, 2014 | access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Mark Swift and Damian Shannon]] choose 1428 Elm Street alongside with Westin Hills Psychiatric Hospital as the token \"classic locations\" representing the franchise in ''Freddy vs. Jason'', while Camp Crystal Lake represented the ''Friday the 13th'' series.<ref name=\"slashofthetitans\" /> The horror blog [https://1428elm.com/ 1428 Elm] and the production company 1428 Films that has produced the documentaries ''[[Never Sleep Again: The Elm Street Legacy]]'' and ''[[Friday the 13th (franchise)#Documentary films|Crystal Lake Memories: The Complete History of Friday the 13th]]'' and helped produced films such as ''[[The Haunting of Sharon Tate]]'' has both derived their names from the fictional house.<ref name=\"neversleepagain\" /> [[Mondo (American company)|Mondo]] created a printing for [[MondoCon]] 2016 based on the 1428 Elm Street for their \u201cHome\u201d series of iconic horror locations,<ref>{{cite web | title=Cool Stuff: Mondo\u2019s \u201cHome\u201d Series Takes You Back To Horror\u2019s Creepiest Houses | url=https://www.slashfilm.com/jason-edmiston-and-ken-taylor-home-prints/ | author=Ethan Anderton | date=November 3, 2016 | access-date=March 11, 2020 | website=Slash Film}}</ref> and the company Hawthorne Village has made a miniature of the \"haunted house\" version of the house as part of their \"''Village of Horror''\" series.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Hawthorne Village of Horror Classics Brought Horror Movie Locales to the Toy Shelf | url=http://www.the13thfloor.tv/2016/07/25/the-hawthorne-village-of-horror-classics-brought-horror-movie-locales-to-the-toy-shelf/ | website=13th Floor | author=John Squires | date=July 25, 2016}}</ref> Fans have also set out to recreate the house through means such as with [[3D rendering]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Speed Build - 1428 Elm street: Nightmare on elm st house | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Lr-DB4bKZE | author=Gemini Simmer | via=[[YouTube]] | date=January 20, 2019 | access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>, with [[Lego]] bricks<ref>{{cite web | title=The HOUSE from A Nightmare on Elm Street film series LEGO MOC (Freddy's House/ Nancy' s House) | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KweFmMQSKgg | author=Mikey J Productions | via=[[YouTube]] | date=February 27, 2017 | access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> or as a [[dollhouse]].<ref>{{cite web | title=1428 Elm Street (Freddy Krueger) | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M7HB1KjDqzI | author=Rickey Williams | via=[[YouTube]] | date=August 26, 2018 | access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> 1428 Elm Street was second on [[GamesRadar+|GamesRadar]]'s list of the \"50 Scariest Horror Movie Houses\", being beaten by the [[Ju-On (franchise)|The Saeki house]].<ref>{{cite web | title=50 Scariest Horror Movie Houses | url=https://www.gamesradar.com/50-scariest-horror-movie-houses/5/ | website=[[GamesRadar+]] | author=Sarah Dobbs | date=March 13, 2014 | access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Because of its iconic status among horror fans, the 1428 North Genesee Avenue house is popularly referred to as the 'Nightmare on Elm Street House'<ref name=\"KPCC\">{{cite web | title='Nightmare' renovation: '1428 Elm Street' sells on Genesee Avenue | url=https://www.scpr.org/blogs/news/2013/03/13/12902/nightmare-renovation-1428-elm-street-sells-on-gene/ | author=Lisa Brenner |  date=March 13, 2013 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | website=[[KPCC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Nightmare on Elm Street House | url=https://www.yelp.com/biz/nightmare-on-elm-street-house-los-angeles?adjust_creative=mapquest&hrid=mPcSkc-omN8kZnNI8jvFDQ | website=[[Yelp]] | access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> and some fans make [[pilgrimage]]s to see the real life location.<ref>{{cite web | title=1428 Elm Street, Springwood, OH: A Pilgrimage To The NIGHTMARE House | url=http://www.the13thfloor.tv/2016/12/27/1428-elm-street-springwood-oh-a-pilgrimage-to-the-nightmare-house/ | website=13th Floor | author=BJ Colangelo | date=December 27, 2016 | access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ihorror\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [[centralwikia:w:c:nightmareonelmstreet:Elm Street House|1428 Elm Street]] at A Nightmare on Elm Street (wiki)\n* [[centralwikia:w:c:fridaythe13th:1428 Elm Street|1428 Elm Street]] at Friday the 13th (wiki)\n* [[centralwikia:w:c:horror:1428 Elm Street|1428 Elm Street]] at Horror Film (wiki)\n\n{{A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n{{authoritycontrol}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional elements introduced in 1984]]\n[[Category:A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Fictional houses]]\n[[Category:Ohio in fiction]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox fictional location\n| name          = 1428 Elm Street\n| image         =\n| image_size    =\n| alt           =\n| caption       =\n| source        = [[A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)|A Nightmare on Elm Street]]\n| alt_name      = [The] Elm Street House\n| first         = ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street]]'' (1984)\n| last          = ''[[Freddy vs Jason]]'' (2003)\n| creator       = [[Wes Craven]]\n| genre         = [[Horror film]]\n| type          = Residential house\n| blank_label1  = Location\n| blank_data1   = Springwood, [[Ohio]]\n| blank_label2  = Street\n| blank_data2   = Elm Street\n| ruler         = \n| characters    = {{bulleted list|[[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Nancy Thompson]]|[[Jesse Walsh]]|[[List of A Nightmare on Elm Street characters#Lori Campbell|Lori Campbell]]|[[Freddy Krueger]]<br>([[#The house as Freddy's home|possibly]])}}\n}}\n\n{{for|the historic house in [[Arkansas]]|Elm Street House}}\n'''1428 Elm Street''', also known as '''[the] Elm Street House''', is a fictional residential house and street address in Springwood, [[Ohio]], and is an important location in the ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)|A Nightmare on Elm Street]]'' [[Media franchise|franchise]], where it's been the home of [[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Nancy Thompson]] and her mother, later [[Jesse Walsh]] and his family, and finally [[List of A Nightmare on Elm Street characters#Lori Campbell|Lori Campbell]] and her father throughout the film series. It has also been hinted at to have been [[Freddy Krueger]]'s home when he was alive. It further appears in some form in nearly all the films as well as literature, comics, video games and music videos. The house, like Nancy, [[Tina Gray (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Tina Gray]], [[Kristen Parker]] as well as their mutual tormentor and eventual murderer [[Freddy Krueger]], were all conceived by the late horror legend [[Wes Craven]].\n\n==Appearances==\n\n===Films===\n\n1428 Elm Street is first introduced in ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street]]'' (1984), where it is owned by Marge Thompson, who lives there with her teenage daughter [[Nancy Thompson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Nancy]]. There is seemingly nothing out of the ordinary about the house at the time, but this changes when Nancy and her friends starts to have a series of nightmares all featuring the same disfigured, menacing stalker, culminating in Nancy's best friend [[Tina Gray (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Tina Gray]] being slaughtered in her bed by an unseen assailer in the Gray's house on the same street. Piecing together the lore surrounding [[Freddy Krueger]], Nancy learns that her parents along with others [[Lynching|lynched]] and torched Freddy to death after he had murdered around 20 kids in the neighborhood; they also hid his old murder weapon, a glove with knives attached to it, in a boiler in the basement of the Thompson's home. Nancy finds a way to bring Freddy out of her dreams and confronts him in 1428 Elm Street, luring him through a series of [[boobytrap]]s and setting him in fire. He is temporarily vanquished when Nancy convince him and herself that he have no power over her unless she believes he has, and tells him that she takes back the energy she gave him.<ref name=\"N1 film\">{{cite AV media|people=[[Wes Craven]] (director)|title=[[A Nightmare on Elm Street]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=[[New Line Cinema]]|date=1984}}</ref> The  comics ''Nightmares on Elm Street'' reveals that after this, Nancy moved away from Springwood and went to college in the span between the first film and ''Dream Warriors''.<ref name=\"comic2\">{{cite comic | writer=Andy Mangels | penciller=Tony Harris | inker=Vickie Williams | editor=David Campiti | story=Eternal Evil | title=Nightmares on Elm Street | volume=1 |issue=#2 | date=November 1991 | publisher=Innovation Publishing | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Comics/nightmares-on-elm-street-2/}}</ref>\n\nThe sequel ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 2: Freddy's Revenge]]'' (1985) insinuates that the house had stood unoccupied following the conclusion of the first film. After about five years, the Walsh family moved in, but Freddy's spirit lingered as a residual memory in the house, geographically restricted to it for the moment, and started to invade the dreams of the new occupant [[Jesse Walsh]] as he did with Nancy, now with the additional goal of [[Demonic possession|possessing]] him and making Jesse kill for him.<ref name=\"N2 film\">{{cite AV media|people=[[Jack Sholder]] (director)|title=[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 2: Freddy's Revenge]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=1985}}</ref>\n\nIn ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 3: Dream Warriors]]'' (1987), Freddy seems to have \"adopted\" the house in the dreamworld, luring his victims there even when their dreams does not start in the house. Freddy increasingly tended to blend the house together with the old factory he worked in and brought his victims to while he was alive; the factory was the place he lured Nancy into in her nightmare in school in the first film.<ref name=\"N3 film\">{{cite video|people=[[Chuck Russell]] (Director)|title=[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 3: Dream Warriors]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=1987}}</ref> By the time of ''[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 4: The Dream Master|The Dream Master]]'', the real life 1428 Elm Street has become an uninhabited and boarded up ghost house since the Walsh's moved out at an unknown date - with ''Dream Warriors'' having left their fates unresolved - and would continue being so for many years. Before the events of ''Dream Warriors'', [[Kristen Parker]] builds a model of the house she keeps seing in her nightmares. After being admitted to and later released from the Westin Hills Asylum, she had come to consider the house to be Freddy's \"home\" due to its reoccurance in her nightmares. Before Freddy kills Kristen, her dreams would see her return to the dream-house and its boiler room many times, even when Freddy was dormant.<ref name=\"N4 film\">{{cite video|people=[[Renny Harlin]] (Director)|title=[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 4: The Dream Master]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=1988}}</ref> Though not seen in reality in ''The Dream Child'', the dream version of the house is part of the vistas seen by [[Alice Johnson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Alice Johnson]] in her struggles with Freddy. By this stage Freddy had further perverted the dream-house into a [[M. C. Escher]]-esque labyrinth by also integrating the Westin Hills Asylum and the Dream Church from the two previous films into it.<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child | type=shooting script | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Files/nightmare-on-elm-street-5-script.pdf | date=1989 | access-date=March 10, 2020 | author=John Skipp, Craig Spector, Leslie Bohem, David J. Schow | via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion}}</ref><ref name=\"N5 film\">{{cite video|people=[[Stephen Hopkins (director)|Stephen Hopkins]] (Director)|title=[[A Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=1989}}</ref> In ''Freddy's Dead'', the house was visited by protagonists such as John Doe and Maggie Burroughs and the film often hinted of the idea that Freddy and his family had once lived there when he was alive.<ref name=\"N6 film\">{{cite video|people=Rachel Talalay (Director)|title=[[Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=1991}}</ref>\n\nThe house also appears in the climax of ''[[Wes Craven's New Nightmare]]'' (1994), when a metafictional [[Heather Langenkamp]] channels her in-universe character Nancy Thompson and Heather's house followingly turn into 1428 Elm Street.<ref name=\"N7 film\">{{cite video |people=Wes Craven (Director) |title=[[Wes Craven's New Nightmare]] |medium=DVD |location=United States |publisher=New Line Cinema |date=1994}}</ref> In ''[[Freddy vs Jason]]'' (2003), the house is occupied by Dr. Campbell and his daughter Lori; Freddy murdered Mrs. Campbell in their bedroom after the events of ''[[Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare]]'' took place.<ref name=\"FvJ film\">{{cite AV media|people=[[Ronny Yu]] (director)|title=[[Freddy vs. Jason]]|medium=DVD|location=United States|publisher=New Line Cinema|date=2003}}</ref> In a scene that was cut from the theatrical film, Lori scratches the repainted door to discover the original red painting underneath.<ref name=\"fvjds\">{{cite web | title=Freddy vs. Jason deleted scene - At death's door | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=-fa-wg0H1Dc | date=April 5, 2008 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | author=[[New Line Cinema]] / Nightmare Companion (uploader) | via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n===Other appearances===\n\n====Halloween Horror Nights====\n\nThe house was one of the haunted houses at [[Universal Orlando]]'s [[Halloween Horror Nights|Halloween Horror Nights: Carnival of Carnage]] in 2007; the exterior had been modeled after the worn down dream version from ''Dream Warriors'' and ''The Dream Master''. It was also recreated for [[Universal Studios Hollywood]]'s 2008 event called \"Nightmare on Elm Street: Home Sweet Hell\"<ref>{{cite web | title=Hollywood horror show isn't for the faint of heart | url=http://archive.vcstar.com/lifestyle/hollywood-horror-show-isnt-for-the-faint-of-heart-ep-372911556-352419501.html | website=[[Ventura County Star]] | author=Rick Bentley | date=October 19, 2008 | access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> The house appeared again as a setting during Halloween Horror Nights 25 in 2015 at its \"Freddy vs Jason\" event.<ref>{{cite web | title=Halloween Horror Nights 25 - Freddy vs Jason | url=https://aminoapps.com/c/horror/page/blog/halloween-horror-nights-25-freddy-vs-jason/J8MF_dur2nog0L7wDjLJg4jbm8N2D2r | date=July 16, 2018 | access-date=March 8, 2020 | author=firstclasshorror | website=Amino Apps}}</ref>\n\n====Literature and comics====\n\nIn the ''Nightmare on Elm Street'' comics first two issues, set in 1990, Nancy Thompson's former roommate Cybil Houch sees the house in her recent nightmares about someone who appears to be [[Jack the Ripper]]; the sight of the house leads her to track down Nancy only to find that she died three years ago. Nancy also uses her own version of the house as her \"safe haven\" in the dream world.<ref name=\"comic1\">{{cite comic | writer=[[Andy Mangels]] | penciller=Tony Harris | inker=Vickie Williams | editor=David Campiti | story=Yours Truly, Freddy Krueger | title=Nightmares on Elm Street | volume=1 |issue=#1 | date=September 1991 | publisher=[[Innovation Publishing]] | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Comics/nightmares-on-elm-street-1/}}</ref><ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite web | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/features/timeline/ | title=Timeline | via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion | access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> The house is seen in ''[[Freddy vs. Jason vs. Ash]]'' #5, where a fight between [[Jason Voorhees]] and [[Ash Williams]] causes it to collapse.<ref>{{cite comic | title=[[Freddy vs. Jason vs. Ash]] | issue=#5 | date=April 2008 | writer=[[Jeff Katz]] | cowriters=James Kuhoric | artist=[[Jason Craig]] | colorist=Thomas Mason | letterer=Jared K. Fletcher | editor=Scott Peterson | publisher=[[WildStorm]]}}</ref>\n\nIn the short story \"Asleep at the Wheel\" by Brian Hodge from the anthology book ''The Nightmares on Elm Street: Freddy Krueger's Seven Sweetest Dreams'' (1991), a band that has named themselves \"Nancy Thompson Gravewatch\" decides to spend the night at 1428 Elm Street, which \"has sat idle and abandoned and vacant and boarded over for years\" as described in the story. The band's idea with staying at the house is to confront their inner darkness and make it their own. They are warned against it by Nancy's ghost, but the band refuses to listen and are picked off one by one by Freddy.<ref name=\"ssd1\">{{cite book | author=Brian Hodge | editor=Martin Harry Greenberg | date=1991-10-15 | title=The Nightmares on Elm Street: Freddy Krueger's Seven Sweetest Dreams | chapter=Asleep at the Wheel | publisher = St. Martin's Press | isbn =0-312-92585-9}}</ref> In the short story \"Dead Highway, Lost Roads\" from the same book the house alongside with most of Elm Street has been leveled to the ground and replaced with a shopping mall to help bury the bad reputation that it had gained; Alice Johnson lives nearby, to keep a vigil on Freddy's activities.<ref name=\"ssd2\">{{cite book | author=Philip Nutman | editor=Martin Harry Greenberg | date=1991-10-15 | title=The Nightmares on Elm Street: Freddy Krueger's Seven Sweetest Dreams | chapter=Dead Highway, Lost Roads | pages=172-239 | publisher=St. Martin's Press | isbn=9780312925857}}</ref> In the novel ''A Nightmare on Elm Street: Suffer the Children'', taking place after the events of ''Freddy vs. Jason'', Lori Campbell has moved out of Springwood and 1428 Elm Street is now occupied by Alexandra Corwin and her mother.<ref>{{cite book | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street: Suffer the Children | author=[[David Bishop (writer)|David Bishop]] | date=April 26, 2005 | isbn=1844161722 | publisher=[[Black Flame (publisher)|Black Flame]] | pages=416}}</ref>\n\n====Video games====\n\nThe house is the central setting of an online game called \"Escape from 1428 Elm Street\".<ref name=\"arcadespot\">{{cite web | title=Escape From 1428 Elm Street | url=https://arcadespot.com/game/escape-from-1428-elm-street/ | type=online game | access-date=March 8, 2020 | website=Arcade Spot}}</ref>\n\n====Music videos====\n\nIn the [[music video]] for [[The Fat Boys]]' ''[[Are You Ready for Freddy]]'', the band has to stay one night in the house of one of the Boys' recently deceased \"Uncle Frederick\".<ref>{{cite web | title=The Fat Boys - Are You Ready For Freddy? | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=XDUl5Ke5jbM | author=[[The Fat Boys]] | date=August 19, 1988 | via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref> The music video for [[Dokken]]'s ''[[Dream Warriors (song)|Dream Warriors]]'' song is mostly set in the nightmare version of the house, as visited by [[Kristen Parker]] in the ''Dream Warriors'' film.<ref name=\"dokken\">{{Cite AV media | title=Dokken \u2013 \"Dream Warriors\" (Official Music Video) | via=YouTube | people=[[George Lynch (musician)|George Lynch]], [[Jeff Pilson]], [[Patricia Arquette]], [[Robert Englund]] | date=February 10, 1987 | access-date=March 16, 2020 | publisher=[[Elektra Records|Elektra]] | medium=music video | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=noLPhZvcBpw}}</ref>\n\n====Unrealized projects====\nThe house has been featured in several alternate screenplays that was never filmed. For the third film which became ''Dream Warriors'', Robert Englund wrote his own treatment ''Freddy's Funhouse'', where Freddy had claimed the house for his own in the dream world, setting up [[booby trap]]s against dreamers like Nancy did against him.<ref>{{cite web | title=Freddy's Funhouse: Digging into Robert Englund's Unmade Treatment for 'Nightmare on Elm Street 3' | url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/editorials/3532787/freddys-funhouse-digging-robert-englunds-unmade-treatment-nightmare-elm-street-3/ | date=November 9, 2018 | author=Nat Brehmer | website=[[Bloody Disgusting]] | access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> In an alternate script for ''A Nightmare on Elm Street 5: The Dream Child'' by John Skipp & Craig Spector, a character\nis painting a drawing of the Elm Street house, only to be interrupted by a bulldozer leveling the legally condemned building to the ground to make way for the Elm St. Mall.<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street V: The Dream Child | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Files/nightmare-on-elm-street-5-original-script.pdf | type=screenplay | author=[[John Skipp]] & Craig Spector | date=January 7, 1989 | access-date=March 17, 2020 | via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion}}</ref> In the original script for ''Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare'' by Michael Almereyda, a character walks up to the house and removes plates of the mailbox with the name Williams, the last owners, to reveal the name Thompson underneath, which in turn has the name Krueger underneath it.<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street 6 | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Files/nightmare-on-elm-street-6-alt-script.pdf | type=screenplay | author=Rachel Talalay and Michael Almereyda | via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion | access-date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> Several alternate drafts for ''Freddy vs Jason'' featured the house, including scripts by [[Peter Briggs]], [[Ethan Reiff and Cyrus Voris|Reiff/Voris]] and Abernathy/[[David J. Schow|Schow]]; in the latter, a rundown 1428 Elm Street is blown up following a shootout between a SWAT team and a twisted Freddy-worshipping cultist group, culminating in the latter detonating a bomb in the basement.<ref name=\"slashofthetitans\">{{cite book | title=Slash of the Titans: The Road to Freddy vs Jason | author=Dustin McNeill | date=March 25, 2017 | publisher=Harker Press | asin=B06XVSCY6C | isbn=0692033491 | url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Slash_of_the_Titans.html?id=omSNAQAACAAJ}}</ref>\n\nIn [[David Bishop (writer)|David Bishop]]'s finished but never published sequel to his novel ''A Nightmare on Elm Street: Suffer the Children'', called ''House of 100 Maniacs'', Alexandra Corwin was deemed insane, incriminated for eight murders in truth committed by Freddy and had to spend five years in a maximum security psychiatric ward before being released, brainwashed into thinking that Freddy was nothing but a delusion of hers. As a final part of her therapy, her psychotherapist convinces her that she must go to her former home, the now once again boarded up 1428 Elm Street (now scheduled for demolition), in order to face her demons. The house however attracts many who are intrigued by its reputation as a haunted house, providing Freddy with yet another batch of victims to slaughter. Alex and a girl named Jenny survives, while in the epilogue the house would finally have been demolished. The unpublished novel would also have established that Freddy did live at 1428 as a child.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Nightmare that never was | url=http://viciousimagery.blogspot.com/2006/11/nightmare-that-never-was.html | website=Vicious Imagery | author=[[David Bishop (writer)|David Bishop]] | date=November 27, 2006 | access-date=March 16, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200316005934/http://viciousimagery.blogspot.com/2006/11/nightmare-that-never-was.html | archive-date=March 16, 2020 | url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Development==\nFrom the first film to the sequels, the Elm Street House develops from simply being the place where the action takes to becoming the embodiment of Freddy in the physical world, taking on the characteristics of a classic [[haunted house]] and acting as a portal between the waking life and the [[Dream world (plot device)|dream world]] when characters steps in through the door of the house.<ref name=\"styleandform\">{{cite book | title=Style and Form in the Hollywood Slasher Film | last=Shimabukuro | first=Karra | editor-last=Clayton | editor-first=Wickham | publisher=[[Palgrave Macmillan]] | year=2016 | isbn=9781137496478 | pages=60-61 | chapter=I Framed Freddy: Functional Aesthetics in the ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' series | chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DWPeCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA49}}</ref> In the original script from ''Dream Warriors'', the house seen by the Elm Street children in their nightmares is revealed to not be 1428 Elm Street, but a ranch house where Freddy was born; this idea was omitted in the theatrical film.<ref name=\"dworiginal\">{{Cite web|url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/Files/nightmare-on-elm-street-3-wes-craven-script.pdf|last1=Craven | first1=Wes | author1-link=Wes Craven | last2=Wagner | first2=Bruce | author2-link=Bruce Wagner | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street 3: Dream Warriors (original script)|date=June 16, 1986|via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion|access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> The novelization ''The Nightmares on Elm Street Parts 1, 2, 3: The Continuing Story'', written by Jeffrey Cooper, uses the original script rather than the film script; thus, the ranch house also appears in the ''Dream Warriors'' chapter in the book.<ref name=\"jcooper\">{{cite book | title=The Nightmares on Elm Street parts 1, 2 & 3: The Continuing Story | chapter=[[centralwikia:w:c:nightmareonelmstreet:A Nightmare on Elm Street 3: Dream Warriors (novelization)|Dream Warriors]] | last=Cooper | isbn=978-0312905170 | first=Jeffrey | publisher=St Martins Pr | date=February 1, 1987}}</ref> A non-canonical alternate backstory for 1428 Elm Street was featured in ''The Life and Death of Freddy Krueger'' contained within Cooper's novelization, where the house is described to have once have been a mental asylum where Freddy was born to an unnamed [[Schizophrenia|schizophrenic]] female patient who died in childbirth;<ref>{{cite web | title=The Life and Death of Freddy Krueger | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/the-life-and-death-of-freddy-krueger/ | date=February 1, 1987 | access-date=March 13, 2020 | via=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion}}</ref> the former asylum at 1428 is also present in Cooper's novelization of ''Dream Warriors'', where it's called the Hathaway House.<ref name=\"jcooper\" />\n\n===Filming locations===\n<!-- Out-of-universe description --->\nThe house from the original film was filmed at a private home in 1428 North Genesee Avenue in [[Los Angeles]]<ref>{{cite web|author=Gary Wayne |url=http://www.seeing-stars.com/Locations/80sLocations2.shtml |title=The Nightmare on Elm Street House (photo) |website=Seeing-stars.com |access-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160404120102/http://www.seeing-stars.com/Locations/80sLocations2.shtml |archivedate=April 14, 2016}}</ref> which was constructed in the year 1919;<ref name=\"horrorenthusiast\">{{cite web | title=Where Is the Real Nightmare On Elm Street House Located? | url=https://horrorenthusiast.com/index.php/bloody-tabloid/nightmare-on-elm-street-franchise/49-where-is-the-real-nightmare-on-elm-street-house-located | date=January 18, 2018 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | website=Horror Enthusiast | author=Mr. Cleaver}}</ref> on the other side of the street stands house 1419 which was used as the Lantz family home in the film, where it was also located on the other side of the street.<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street (1984) | url=http://www.set-jetter.com/ontheset/anightmareonelmstreet | date=July 6, 2015 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | website=Jet-Setter}}</ref> House 1428 was also used in ''Freddy's Revenge'' and ''Wes Craven's New Nightmare''.<ref name=\"1428comp\">{{cite web | title=1428 Elm Street | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/features/1428-elm-street/ | website=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion | access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> On [[Bloody Disgusting]], it has been suggested that the house was also used for pickup scenes in the extended TV version of the original ''[[Halloween (1978 film)|Halloween]]'' film by [[John Carpenter]], pointing out the common presence of a decorative wooden horse in the filmed scenes and the pre-renovation house at 1428 North Genesee Avenue as a clue to this.<ref>{{cite web | title=Was the Iconic \u2018Nightmare on Elm Street\u2019 House Used Years Prior in \u2018Halloween\u2019? | url=https://bloody-disgusting.com/movie/3591404/iconic-nightmare-elm-street-house-used-years-prior-halloween/ | date=October 28, 2019 | access-date=March 8, 2020 | author=Alex Aronson | website=[[Bloody Disgusting]]}}</ref> Sean Clark, host of ''Horrors Hallowed Grounds'', was able to visit the house in 2006 before massive renovations completely erased any likeness to the interior as seen in the films. According to Clark, Nancy's room as seen in ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'' had not been a room in the actual house, but one inside a studio set. Carpenter however had gained permission to film inside the actual house, whereas [[Heather Langenkamp]] as Nancy was only inside the house at 1428 North Genesee Avenue for scenes where she's looking out from her bedroom window.<ref>{{cite web | title=Evidence Suggests \u2018A Nightmare On Elm Street\u2019 House Is In \u2018Halloween\u2019 | url=https://www.screengeek.net/2019/10/29/a-nightmare-on-elm-street-house-halloween-movie/ | author=Jacob Dressler | website=Screen Geek | date=October 29, 2019 | access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Someone was asking how I found out that Nancy's house... | url=https://www.facebook.com/malfuncsean/posts/10155799496887031 | author=Sean Clark | via=[[Facebook]] | date=October 23, 2018 | access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe house was put up for sale during 2006.<ref>{{cite web | title=For Sale: Nightmare on Elm Street House | url=http://www.cinematical.com/2006/09/25/for-sale-nightmare-on-elm-street-house/ | date=September 25, 2006 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070509063149/http://www.cinematical.com/2006/09/25/for-sale-nightmare-on-elm-street-house/ | archive-date=May 9, 2007 | url-status=dead | website=Cinematical}}</ref> It was in a state of negligence and worn down when Angie Hill bought it in 2008; she paid $1.15 million for the house then and began a year-long renovation.<ref name=\"ttred\">{{cite web | title=Sold Fast! The Nightmare on Elm Street House! | url=https://www.toptenrealestatedeals.com/weekly-ten-best-home-deals/home/sold-fast-the-nightmare-on-elm-street-house | website=TopTenRealEstateDeals | access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> According to Hill, the previous owners had neglected it to such an extant that it might have been the slummiest house on the street. She preserved its facade throughout the renovation to retain much of its original looks.<ref name=\"horrorenthusiast\" /> Hill renovated as much as 90% of the original interior.<ref>{{cite web | title=1428 North Genesee Avenue Featured on Aol Real Estate | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/1428-north-genesee-avenue-featured-on-aol-real-estate/ | date=October 27, 2012 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | website=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion}}</ref> The house switched owners in 2013 for the price of $2.1 million.<ref name=\"ttred\" /> Heather Langenkamp and Sean Clark visited the house at 1428 North Genesee Avenue in the franchise documentary ''[[Never Sleep Again: The Elm Street Legacy]]'' from 2010, where Hill explains that the original numbers spelling out 1428 had been stolen; the original font could not be replaced as it was no longer being manifactured.<ref name=\"neversleepagain\">{{cite web | title=Never Sleep Again: The Elm Street Legacy | url=https://www.amazon.com/Never-Sleep-Again-Street-Blu-ray/dp/B00G6TPQ1C/ | format=blu-ray | people=Robert Englund, Heather Langenkamp, Wes Craven, Lisa Wilcox, Alice Cooper, Andrew Kasch, Daniel Farrands, Thommy Hutson |website=Amazon.com |date=May 4, 2010 |accessdate=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Heather and [[Robert Englund]] (Freddy Krueger) also revisited the house together in 2013,<ref>{{cite web | title='Nightmare' stars Robert Englund & Heather Langenkamp Return to Elm Street | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Hlmdt5VE3Lk | date=March 8, 2013 | access-date=March 8, 2020 | author=David Weiner | via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>, while [[Lisa Wilcox]] (Alice Johnson) visited it in 2017.<ref>{{cite web | title=Join Lisa Wilcox (Alice Johnson) at the original Nightmare on Elm Street house. Los Angeles, CA | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SCuq_evUX20 | author=Lisa Wilcox | date=April 27, 2017 | access-date=March 8, 2020 | via=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\nThe color of the front door was blue in ''A Nightmare on Elm Street'', but was painted blood red for ''Freddy's Revenge''; red would remain the preferred color throughout the franchise except for when Wes Craven had it restored to blue for ''[[Wes Craven's New Nightmare|New Nightmare]]'',<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street 2: Freddy's Revenge (1985) | url=http://www.set-jetter.com/ontheset/freddysrevenge | date=June 23, 2015 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | website=Set-Jetter}}</ref><ref name=\"N7 film\" /> which was once again filmed at 1428 North Genesee Avenue, whereas parts 3-6 had all used facade sets for the likeness of the house's front.<ref name=\"1428comp\" /> ''Freddy vs. Jason'' filmed with a different house than the other films as it was filmed in [[Vancouver]] and not Los Angeles.<ref>{{cite web | title=Freddy vs. Jason (2003) | url=http://www.set-jetter.com/ontheset/freddyvsjason | date=November 28, 2015 | access-date=March 8, 2020 | website=Set-Jetter}}</ref> In the film, the door was originally red but had been painted over with yellow color.<ref name=\"fvjds\" /> According to production designer John Willett, the process of a finding a matching house in Vancouver was very difficult and earlier film teams from the ''Nightmare'' series had not preserved accurate drawing records that the new team could follow, but they eventually found a house that was an 80% match of its Los Angeles predecessor, and shot the scenes inside the house instead of a stage due to budget concerns.<ref name=\"CLM_book\">{{cite book|last = Bracke|first = Peter|title = Crystal Lake Memories - The Complete History of Friday the 13th|publisher = Titan Books|date = 2006-10-11|location = [[United Kingdom]]|page = 276|isbn = 1-84576-343-2}}</ref>\n\n==Description==\n\n===Setting===\n<!-- In-universe description --->\nThe house is located on Elm Street in the fictional town of Springwood in [[Ohio]]. In the script for the 1984 film, Wes Craven mentions Los Angeles in California as the setting and has Elm Street located in an unnamed suburb, but this information is left out of the film. The change to Ohio was possibly done as a homage to Wes Craven, who was born in Cleveland in Ohio.<ref>{{cite web | title=Series FAQ | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/features/series-faq/#04 | access-date=March 13, 2020 | website=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion}}</ref> The name Springwood and its change from suburb to town was introduced in ''Freddy's Revenge''.<ref name=\"N2 film\" /> The script to ''[[Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare]]'' humorously refers to Elm Street as \"''The supreme \"bad place\" of the universe. A street that ranks right there with \"The [[Flying Dutchman]]\", and \"The [[Bermuda Triangle]]\". The street that makes \"[[The Amityville Horror]]\" look like a Long Island tupperware party''.\"<ref>{{cite web | title=Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare \u2014 Scripts | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/films/freddys-dead-the-final-nightmare/freddys-dead-the-final-nightmare-scripts/ | website=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion | access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> Many of the other characters in the series lives on Elm Street, such as Glen Lantz, Rick and [[Alice Johnson (A Nightmare on Elm Street)|Alice Johnson]], who refers to the child murders by pre-lynching Freddy Krueger to have happened \"right here on Elm Street\".<ref name=\"N5 film\" />\n\n===The house as Freddy's home===\n\nIn ''The Dream Master'', Kristen Parker refers to 1428 Elm Street as Freddy's home while visiting it in real life with her friends.<ref name=\"N4 film\" /> Halloween Horror Nights and various media such as \"Escape from 1428 Elm Street\" propagates the idea of the Thompson/Walsh house also having been Freddy's house.<ref name=\"arcadespot\" /> In the book \"''The Nightmare Never Ends: The Official History of Freddy Krueger and the \u2018Nightmare on Elm Street\u2019 Films''\", [[Andy Mangels]] supplies a \"Key to Map of Springwood\" which lists Elm Street residents and lists the Krueger's as living on 1665 Elm Street,<ref>{{cite web | title=Official map of Freddy Krueger\u2019s hometown of Springwood | url=https://see-throughiron.tumblr.com/post/127109586420/official-map-of-freddy-kruegers-hometown-of | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200310221528/https://see-throughiron.tumblr.com/post/127109586420/official-map-of-freddy-kruegers-hometown-of | archive-date=March 10, 2020 | url-status=live | date=August 19, 2015 | access-date=March 10, 2020 | author=[[Andy Mangels]] | via=see-throughiron @ [[Tumblr]]}}</ref> and further argues that the houses might only look similar due to having the same designers, but the webmaster of Nightmare on Elm Street Companion argues that ''Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare'' definitely portrayed Freddy's original home as being in fact 1428 Elm Street, including a deleted scene where Maggie finds a hidden room in the basement of the house where Freddy kept all his weapons and tools designed for murder when he lived, and that the franchise has consistently referred to the house as \"Freddy's house\".<ref>{{cite web | title=The House Where Freddy Lives | url=http://nightmareonelmstreetfilms.com/site/the-house-where-freddy-lives/ | website=Nightmare on Elm Street Companion | access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> ''A Nightmare on Elm Street: The Beginning'', Andy Mangels' comic book sequel to ''Freddy's Dead: The Final Nightmare'' that was never finished due to the bankruptcy of [[Innovation Publishing]] and only saw two issues released, would have established that the reason for why Freddy is consistently drawn to 1428 Elm Street is because his original glove is hidden in its cellar.<ref>{{cite web | title=A Nightmare on Elm Street: The Beginning (plot) | url=http://www.andymangels.com/Beginning_plot.pdf | author=[[Andy Mangels]] | website=Andymangels.com | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091007013617/http://www.andymangels.com/Beginning_plot.pdf | date=October 22, 1991 | archive-date=October 7, 2009 | url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nThe house has been referred to as \"beyond iconic\",<ref name=\"cosplaychris\">{{cite web | title=Filming Locations: A Nightmare on Elm Street (1984) | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?time_continue=123&v=22WnYtcWQgI&feature=emb_logo | author=Cosplay Chris | via=[[YouTube]] | date=July 30, 2018 | access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> \"one of the most legendary horror homes in movies\"<ref name=\"aol2012\">{{cite web | title=The House in 'A Nightmare on Elm Street' Was Truly Scary Before Angie Hill Rehabbed It | url=http://realestate.aol.com/blog/2012/10/12/the-house-in-a-nightmare-on-elm-street-was-truly-scary-before/ | author=Graham Wood | website=Aol Real Estate | date=October 12, 2012 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121213171733/http://realestate.aol.com/blog/2012/10/12/the-house-in-a-nightmare-on-elm-street-was-truly-scary-before/ | archive-date=December 13, 2012 | url-status=dead}}</ref> and \"the star of ''A Nightmare on Elm Street''\".<ref name=\"ihorror\">{{cite web | title=Every Town Has An Elm Street: A Look At 1428 Elm Street. | url=https://www.ihorror.com/every-town-has-an-elm-street-a-look-at-1428-elm-street/ | website=iHorror | author=Ryan T. Cusick | date=June 22, 2014 | access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Mark Swift and Damian Shannon]] choose 1428 Elm Street alongside with Westin Hills Psychiatric Hospital as the token \"classic locations\" representing the franchise in ''Freddy vs. Jason'', while Camp Crystal Lake represented the ''Friday the 13th'' series.<ref name=\"slashofthetitans\" /> The horror blog [https://1428elm.com/ 1428 Elm] and the production company 1428 Films that has produced the documentaries ''[[Never Sleep Again: The Elm Street Legacy]]'' and ''[[Friday the 13th (franchise)#Documentary films|Crystal Lake Memories: The Complete History of Friday the 13th]]'' and helped produced films such as ''[[The Haunting of Sharon Tate]]'' has both derived their names from the fictional house.<ref name=\"neversleepagain\" /> [[Mondo (American company)|Mondo]] created a printing for [[MondoCon]] 2016 based on the 1428 Elm Street for their \u201cHome\u201d series of iconic horror locations,<ref>{{cite web | title=Cool Stuff: Mondo\u2019s \u201cHome\u201d Series Takes You Back To Horror\u2019s Creepiest Houses | url=https://www.slashfilm.com/jason-edmiston-and-ken-taylor-home-prints/ | author=Ethan Anderton | date=November 3, 2016 | access-date=March 11, 2020 | website=Slash Film}}</ref> and the company Hawthorne Village has made a miniature of the \"haunted house\" version of the house as part of their \"''Village of Horror''\" series.<ref>{{cite web | title=The Hawthorne Village of Horror Classics Brought Horror Movie Locales to the Toy Shelf | url=http://www.the13thfloor.tv/2016/07/25/the-hawthorne-village-of-horror-classics-brought-horror-movie-locales-to-the-toy-shelf/ | website=13th Floor | author=John Squires | date=July 25, 2016}}</ref> Fans have also set out to recreate the house through means such as with [[3D rendering]]<ref>{{cite web | title=Speed Build - 1428 Elm street: Nightmare on elm st house | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Lr-DB4bKZE | author=Gemini Simmer | via=[[YouTube]] | date=January 20, 2019 | access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>, with [[Lego]] bricks<ref>{{cite web | title=The HOUSE from A Nightmare on Elm Street film series LEGO MOC (Freddy's House/ Nancy' s House) | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KweFmMQSKgg | author=Mikey J Productions | via=[[YouTube]] | date=February 27, 2017 | access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> or as a [[dollhouse]].<ref>{{cite web | title=1428 Elm Street (Freddy Krueger) | url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=M7HB1KjDqzI | author=Rickey Williams | via=[[YouTube]] | date=August 26, 2018 | access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> 1428 Elm Street was second on [[GamesRadar+|GamesRadar]]'s list of the \"50 Scariest Horror Movie Houses\", being beaten by the [[Ju-On (franchise)|The Saeki house]].<ref>{{cite web | title=50 Scariest Horror Movie Houses | url=https://www.gamesradar.com/50-scariest-horror-movie-houses/5/ | website=[[GamesRadar+]] | author=Sarah Dobbs | date=March 13, 2014 | access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Because of its iconic status among horror fans, the 1428 North Genesee Avenue house is popularly referred to as the 'Nightmare on Elm Street House'<ref name=\"KPCC\">{{cite web | title='Nightmare' renovation: '1428 Elm Street' sells on Genesee Avenue | url=https://www.scpr.org/blogs/news/2013/03/13/12902/nightmare-renovation-1428-elm-street-sells-on-gene/ | author=Lisa Brenner |  date=March 13, 2013 | access-date=March 9, 2020 | website=[[KPCC]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Nightmare on Elm Street House | url=https://www.yelp.com/biz/nightmare-on-elm-street-house-los-angeles?adjust_creative=mapquest&hrid=mPcSkc-omN8kZnNI8jvFDQ | website=[[Yelp]] | access-date=March 8, 2020}}</ref> and some fans make [[pilgrimage]]s to see the real life location.<ref>{{cite web | title=1428 Elm Street, Springwood, OH: A Pilgrimage To The NIGHTMARE House | url=http://www.the13thfloor.tv/2016/12/27/1428-elm-street-springwood-oh-a-pilgrimage-to-the-nightmare-house/ | website=13th Floor | author=BJ Colangelo | date=December 27, 2016 | access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"ihorror\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n\n* [[centralwikia:w:c:nightmareonelmstreet:Elm Street House|1428 Elm Street]] at A Nightmare on Elm Street (wiki)\n* [[centralwikia:w:c:fridaythe13th:1428 Elm Street|1428 Elm Street]] at Friday the 13th (wiki)\n* [[centralwikia:w:c:horror:1428 Elm Street|1428 Elm Street]] at Horror Film (wiki)\n\n{{A Nightmare on Elm Street}}\n{{authoritycontrol}}\n\n[[Category:Fictional elements introduced in 1984]]\n[[Category:A Nightmare on Elm Street (franchise)]]\n[[Category:Fictional houses]]\n[[Category:Ohio in fiction]]\n", "name_user": "WereSpielChequers", "label": "safe", "comment": "Typo fixing,typo(s) fixed: manifactured \u2192 manufactured, seing \u2192 seeing, reoccurance \u2192 reoccurrence", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1428_Elm_Street"}
